President Joe Biden addressed the Building Trades Union at the Washington Hilton Hotel in Washington, D.C. He thanked the union for their support and acknowledged the importance of unions in his own political career. Biden emphasized his commitment to being the most pro-union President in American history and praised the work of union workers, stating that they are the best workers in the world. He highlighted the progress made in job creation and economic growth under his administration, but acknowledged that there is more work to be done. Biden discussed his infrastructure plan and the importance of rebuilding America's infrastructure, creating jobs, and buying American products. He also addressed issues such as inflation, prescription drug prices, and tax reforms, calling for fair taxation and a minimum tax for billionaires. Biden criticized Republicans for their opposition to his policies and warned against the consequences of defaulting on the national debt. He concluded by expressing his optimism for America's future and urging unity and cooperation to continue making progress.